## Code Evidence

### 1. Authentication & Session Management (module_1.txt)

```rust
// File: /app/project/src/module_1.txt
// Lines: 14-27 (Service Description)
//!
//! EduPulse Live – Session-based Authentication Service.
//!
//! Responsibilities:
//! ● Secure user registration (bcrypt password hashing)
//! ● JWT-based authentication with refresh tokens
//! ● Session storage in Redis with configurable TTL
//! ● Role-based access control (RBAC)
//!
//! The module exposes an HTTP middleware and a standalone service
//! that can be used from Axum, Actix-web or any other async framework.
```

```rust
// File: /app/project/src/module_1.txt
// Lines: 133-157 (JWT Authentication)
pub async fn login(
    &self,
    email: &str,
    password_raw: &str,
) -> Result<AuthResponse, AuthError> {
    // 1. Find user by email
    let user = self
        .repo
        .find_by_email(email)
        .await?
        .ok_or(AuthError::InvalidCredentials)?;

    // 2. Verify password hash (bcrypt)
    bcrypt::verify(password_raw, &user.password_hash)?;

    // 3. Mint JWT tokens (access + refresh)
    let access_token = self.mint_access_token(&user)?;
    let refresh_token = self.mint_refresh_token(&user)?;

    // 4. Create a server-side session in Redis
    let session = Session::new(user.id, user.role.clone(), self.session_ttl);
    self.sessions.set(&session).await?;

    Ok(AuthResponse {
        access_token,
        refresh_token,
        session_id: session.id,
    })
}
```

### 2. Event Publishing Infrastructure (module_4.txt)

```rust
// File: /app/project/src/module_4.txt
// Lines: 1-20 (Module Description)
//! src/module_4.rs
//!
//! EduPulse Live – Event-Sourcing Core
//!
//! This module provides the building blocks for implementing event-sourced
//! aggregates and reliable message publishing within the "EduPulse Live"
//! platform.  Key components:
//!
//! ● `DomainEvent` – trait marking an event eligible for persistence/publishing
//! ● `EventStore` – trait for persisting events (Postgres implementation)
//! ● `EventPublisher` – trait for pushing events to the message bus (NATS impl)
//! ● `OutboxForwarder` – worker that drains the "outbox" table and publishes
//!
//! The design follows the Outbox Pattern to guarantee *exactly-once* delivery
//! even when the primary DB and the message broker are separate systems.
```

```rust
// File: /app/project/src/module_4.txt
// Lines: 240-268 (NATS JetStream Publisher)
pub struct NatsJsEventPublisher {
    nc: Arc<nats::asynk::Connection>,
    jetstream: async_nats::jetstream::Context,
}

impl NatsJsEventPublisher {
    pub async fn connect(url: &str, stream_name: &str) -> Result<Self, PublishError> {
        let nc = nats::asynk::connect(url)
            .await
            .map_err(|e| PublishError::Connection(e.to_string()))?;
        let js = async_nats::jetstream::new(nc.clone());

        // Ensure stream exists with sensible defaults
        js.get_or_create_stream(async_nats::jetstream::stream::Config {
            name: stream_name.to_string(),
            subjects: vec![format!("{stream_name}.>")],
            max_age: Duration::from_secs(60 * 60 * 24 * 7), // 7 days
            ..Default::default()
        })
        .await
        .map_err(|e| PublishError::JetStream(e.to_string()))?;

        Ok(Self {
            nc: Arc::new(nc),
            jetstream: js,
        })
    }
}
```

### 3. Service Layer Pattern (module_33.txt)

```rust
// File: /app/project/src/module_33.txt
// Lines: 238-280 (Service Layer)
pub struct PulseService<R: PulseRepository, P: EventPublisher> {
    repo: R,
    publisher: P,
    broker_timeout: Duration,
}

impl<R: PulseRepository, P: EventPublisher> PulseService<R, P> {
    /// Create a Pulse and broadcast a `PulseCreated` domain event.
    ///
    /// The method is transactional at the application level. If the event
    /// cannot be published within [`broker_timeout`], the database insert is
    /// **not** rolled back (best-effort), but the caller is informed through
    /// an error.
    pub async fn create_pulse(&self, new: &NewPulse<'_>) -> Result<LearningPulse, PulseError> {
        let pulse = self.repo.create(new).await?;

        let event = DomainEvent::PulseCreated(PulseCreated {
            pulse_id: pulse.id,
            teacher_id: pulse.teacher_id,
            occurred_at: Utc::now(),
        });

        // We don't want to await forever; use `tokio::time::timeout`.
        timeout(self.broker_timeout, self.publisher.publish(&event))
            .await
            .map_err(|_| PulseError::Timeout)??;

        Ok(pulse)
    }
}
```

### 4. Event Consumer Pattern (module_15.txt)

```rust
// File: /app/project/src/module_15.txt
// Lines: 1-25 (Event Consumer Service)
//! src/module_15.rs
//!
//! Badge-Awarding Worker
//! ---------------------
//! This module implements a background worker that listens to domain events and
//! awards badges to users when they satisfy certain achievement criteria.  It
//! showcases:
//!  • Event-driven, fully asynchronous architecture
//!  • Clean separation of Event-handling / Repository / Service concerns
//!  • Structured logging via `tracing`
//!  • Strong typing for event payloads
//!
//! In production this worker would be deployed as a separate binary or k8s job,
//! connected to the message broker (NATS / RabbitMQ / Kafka).  For testability
//! the broker abstraction is hidden behind an `EventConsumer` trait.
```

```rust
// File: /app/project/src/module_15.txt
// Lines: 180-210 (Event Handling Logic)
async fn handle_event(
    &self,
    envelope: EventEnvelope<'_>,
) -> Result<(), WorkerError> {
    match &envelope.payload {
        DomainEvent::QuizSubmitted {
            student_id,
            score,
            ..
        } if *score >= 90.0 => {
            // Award "Quiz Ace" badge
            let badge = Badge::new(
                *student_id,
                BadgeKind::QuizAce,
                "Scored ≥90% on a quiz",
            );
            self.badge_repo.save(badge).await?;
            info!(user_id = %student_id, "Awarded QuizAce badge");
        }
        DomainEvent::PeerFeedbackGiven {
            reviewer_id, ..
        } => {
            // Award "Helpful Peer" badge after 5 feedbacks
            let count = self.badge_repo.count_by_user(*reviewer_id).await?;
            if count >= 5 {
                let badge = Badge::new(*reviewer_id, BadgeKind::HelpfulPeer, "Gave 5+ peer feedbacks");
                self.badge_repo.save(badge).await?;
            }
        }
        _ => {}
    }
    Ok(())
}
```

